1) How we can create custom functional interface?
A Custom Functional Interface is an interface that contains only one abstract method.
It is mainly used to support Lambda Expressions and Method References introduced in Java 8.
We can create it using the @FunctionalInterface annotation, which provides compile-time validation.
A functional interface can also contain multiple default and static methods.
If an interface contains more than one abstract method, it is not considered a functional interface.
Custom functional interfaces are commonly used to implement custom business logic like validation, payment processing, and notifications.
They help reduce boilerplate code and make the code more readable and maintainable.
Examples of built-in functional interfaces are Runnable, Callable, Predicate, Function, and Consumer.

The word “Functional” in Functional Interface means the interface represents a single function or single behavior.
It contains only one abstract method, so it performs one specific task.

We need Functional Interfaces to:
write code using Lambda Expressions
reduce boilerplate code
pass behavior/functionality as input
make code cleaner and more flexible

Example:
Instead of creating a separate class for one small task, we can directly write:
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Task Running");
Here, Runnable is a functional interface representing one function: run().

2) What are the functional interface methods
Most used Functional Interfaces and their abstract methods:
->Predicate<T> → boolean test(T t)
Used for condition checking.
->Consumer<T> → void accept(T t)
Used to consume/process data.
->Supplier<T> → T get()
Used to supply/return data.
->Function<T,R> → R apply(T t)
Used to transform one object into another.
->Runnable → void run()
Used in multithreading to define a task.
->Callable<V> → V call()
Similar to Runnable, but returns value and can throw exception.
->Comparator<T> → int compare(T o1, T o2)
Used for custom sorting.
